		<title>
		By: Robert Crafr		</title>
		<link>https://jamesclear.vercel.app/heroin-habits#comment-12773</link>

		<dc:creator><![CDATA[Robert Crafr]]></dc:creator>
		<pubDate>Mon, 10 Nov 2014 01:53:37 +0000</pubDate>
		<guid isPermaLink="false">https://jamesclear-com.uar9g7bv-liquidwebsites.com/?p=6040#comment-12773</guid>

					<description><![CDATA[I appreciate the article.  As a Vietnam veteran, and one who spent an interim assignment at the US Army Drug Rehab Center in DaNang in &#039;71, I can offer a point not covered above. 

Under the provisions of the UCMJ (Uniform Code of Military Justice),  the penalties for possession/use of Marijuana and Heroin were identical.   Smoking Heroin was detectable only by urinalysis while smoking Marijuana was obvious to any in the immediate area at the time of use. 

The end result was that the majority of Heroin &quot;addicts&quot; were recreational Marijuana users who chose the less detectable high.   Further, the military definition of an &quot;addict&quot; was not that of civilian medicine -- a positive urinalysis prior to DEROS (date of estimated return from overseas) was sufficient. 

Thus, Heroin &quot;addiction&quot;  in RVN was less a reflection of addictive personality than of evasion of the penalties of recreational drug use. 

That said, many who used drugs recreationally did so to escape the stress of combat and/or the tedium between periods of combat. 

On return from Vietnam, that stress disappeared along with the desire/need for drugs for the majority of returnees; with the exception of those with PTSD or addictive personality types. 

Thus, the article&#039;s premise of changing environments is valid,  but for reasons rather unique to the situation.]]></description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<p>I appreciate the article.  As a Vietnam veteran, and one who spent an interim assignment at the US Army Drug Rehab Center in DaNang in &#8217;71, I can offer a point not covered above. </p>
<p>Under the provisions of the UCMJ (Uniform Code of Military Justice),  the penalties for possession/use of Marijuana and Heroin were identical.   Smoking Heroin was detectable only by urinalysis while smoking Marijuana was obvious to any in the immediate area at the time of use. </p>
<p>The end result was that the majority of Heroin &#8220;addicts&#8221; were recreational Marijuana users who chose the less detectable high.   Further, the military definition of an &#8220;addict&#8221; was not that of civilian medicine &#8212; a positive urinalysis prior to DEROS (date of estimated return from overseas) was sufficient. </p>
<p>Thus, Heroin &#8220;addiction&#8221;  in RVN was less a reflection of addictive personality than of evasion of the penalties of recreational drug use. </p>
<p>That said, many who used drugs recreationally did so to escape the stress of combat and/or the tedium between periods of combat. </p>
<p>On return from Vietnam, that stress disappeared along with the desire/need for drugs for the majority of returnees; with the exception of those with PTSD or addictive personality types. </p>
<p>Thus, the article&#8217;s premise of changing environments is valid,  but for reasons rather unique to the situation.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
		
